(42, 22, 14, 40, 26, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of the Last Supper', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of Jesus with the twelve apostles at a significant meal. The phrase ''he sat down with the twelve'' in both accounts highlights this moment of communion.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 14, 41, 14, 17, 17, 'the twelve', 'Connection of the Twelve Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''the twelve'' during significant moments. Luke 22:14 mentions Jesus sitting down with the twelve apostles, while Mark 14:17 indicates that he comes with the twelve in the evening.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 14, 5, 16, 6, 7, 'the twelve apostles with him', 'Passover and Gathering', 'This connection highlights the gathering of the apostles for the Passover meal, paralleling the command in Deuteronomy to sacrifice the Passover at a chosen place. Both passages emphasize the significance of communal observance during the Passover season.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 14, 41, 6, 30, 30, 'the twelve apostles with him', 'Gathering of the Apostles', 'This connection highlights the gathering of the apostles with Jesus. Both passages emphasize the presence of the apostles as they come together to share their experiences with Him.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 15, 42, 12, 50, 50, 'before I suffer', 'Connection of Suffering and Preparation', 'Both passages emphasize a sense of urgency and preparation for suffering. In Luke 22:15, the desire to partake in the Passover signifies a pivotal moment before suffering, while Luke 12:50 expresses a straitened feeling until the baptism of suffering is accomplished.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 15, 43, 4, 34, 34, 'With desire I have desired', 'Desire and Will of God', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' deep desire to fulfill God''s will. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the importance of completing a significant task, whether it is the Passover meal or doing the will of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 15, 43, 13, 1, 1, 'passover', 'Connection of Passover and Love', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the Passover in relation to Jesus'' impending suffering and his deep love for his disciples. Luke highlights Jesus'' desire to share the Passover meal, while John underscores his love for them as he prepares for his departure.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 15, 43, 17, 1, 1, 'before I suffer', 'Desire and Hour of Suffering', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' anticipation of his suffering and the significance of the Passover meal. Both passages emphasize a pivotal moment in Jesus'' ministry, where he expresses a deep desire before facing his impending sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 42, 14, 15, 15, 'eat thereof, until it be fulfilled', 'Eating in the Kingdom of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of eating in the kingdom of God. Both passages refer to the significance of sharing a meal in the eschatological context, emphasizing the anticipation of fulfillment in God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 66, 19, 9, 9, 'until it be fulfilled in the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Supper Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of a divine banquet. In Luke, the anticipation of fulfillment in the kingdom of God parallels the blessed invitation to the marriage supper of the Lamb in Revelation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 42, 22, 30, 30, 'fulfilled in the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Kingdom Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of God. Both passages emphasize the future fulfillment of eating and drinking in the kingdom, linking the present moment with the anticipated future celebration.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 43, 6, 50, 58, 'fulfilled in the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Bread and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of bread as a source of life. Luke speaks of fulfillment in the kingdom of God, while John describes Jesus as the living bread that grants eternal life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 46, 5, 7, 8, 'until it be fulfilled in the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Passover and Unleavened Bread', 'This connection highlights the theme of purification and fulfillment. Both passages emphasize the significance of being ''unleavened'' and the sacrificial role of Christ as the Passover.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 43, 6, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Eternal Sustenance', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring sustenance. Both passages emphasize the importance of seeking spiritual nourishment that leads to everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 16, 44, 10, 41, 41, NULL, 'Connection of Eating and Witnessing', 'This connection highlights the theme of eating and drinking with Jesus, which signifies fellowship and communion. In Luke 22:16, Jesus speaks of not eating until the kingdom is fulfilled, while Acts 10:41 refers to those who ate and drank with him after his resurrection, emphasizing the continuity of this fellowship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 19, 116, 13, 13, 'Take this, and divide it among yourselves', 'Connection of Cups in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking a cup, symbolizing a significant moment of communion and salvation. The cup in Luke represents sharing among believers, while the cup in Psalms signifies a personal acceptance of salvation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 42, 22, 19, 19, 'gave thanks', 'Connection of Communion Elements', 'Both passages emphasize the act of giving thanks and sharing elements during the Last Supper. The cup in verse 17 and the bread in verse 19 highlight the significance of these elements in the context of remembrance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 5, 8, 10, 10, NULL, 'Blessing and Thanksgiving Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of giving thanks after receiving blessings. Both passages emphasize the act of blessing God in response to abundance, whether it be through sharing a cup or recognizing the good land.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 24, 16, 7, 7, 'the cup', 'Connection of Cups in Mourning', 'This connection highlights the theme of the cup as a symbol of both consolation and division. In Luke, the cup is shared among the disciples, while in Jeremiah, the cup is withheld as a form of mourning and lack of consolation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 42, 9, 16, 16, 'Take this, and divide it among yourselves', 'Blessing and Sharing', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking, blessing, and distributing food. In Luke 22:17, the cup is divided among the disciples, while in Luke 9:16, the loaves and fishes are given to the disciples to share with the multitude.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 45, 14, 6, 6, NULL, 'Thanksgiving in Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of giving thanks in both passages. In Luke, Jesus gives thanks before sharing the cup, while Romans emphasizes giving thanks in eating and observing days.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 17, 54, 4, 4, 5, 'gave thanks', 'Thanksgiving in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of thanksgiving in both passages. Luke 22:17 emphasizes giving thanks during the Last Supper, while 1 Timothy 4:4-5 states that all creatures are good when received with thanksgiving.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 40, 26, 29, 29, 'fruit of the vine', 'Connection of Kingdom References', 'Both passages emphasize the ''fruit of the vine'' and the coming ''kingdom.'' This connection highlights the anticipation of a future celebration in God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 42, 22, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Kingdom Fulfillment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not partaking in the fruit of the vine until the kingdom of God is realized. This connection highlights the anticipation of fulfillment in the kingdom, linking the act of eating and drinking to its future realization.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 23, 55, 1, 1, 'fruit of the vine', 'Connection of Thirst and Wine', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of thirst and the provision of wine. Luke speaks of not drinking wine until the kingdom comes, while Isaiah invites those who thirst to come and buy wine without price.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 41, 14, 25, 25, 'fruit of the vine', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''fruit of the vine'' and the anticipation of drinking it in the ''kingdom of God.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of future fulfillment and celebration in God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 7, 9, 13, 13, 'fruit of the vine', 'Connection of Wine and Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the significance of wine in both passages. In Luke, the absence of drinking wine until the kingdom comes suggests a future fulfillment, while in Judges, the vine''s wine is described as something that ''cheereth God and man.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 20, 31, 6, 7, 'fruit of the vine', 'Connection Between Wine and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the use of wine in both passages as a means of addressing human suffering. In Luke, the absence of wine signifies a future hope, while in Proverbs, wine is offered to alleviate the burdens of those in distress.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 18, 22, 5, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Wine Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of drinking wine, symbolizing joy and communion. Luke 22:18 speaks of abstaining from wine until the kingdom comes, while Song of Solomon 5:1 describes drinking wine abundantly in a celebratory context.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
